</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">&nbsp; &nbsp;- Final aut=
hority for meeting cancellations should rest with the Planning Commission C=
hairperson<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">&nbsp; &nbsp;- Decisions=
 regarding joint meetings with the Board of Trustees should be determined b=
y the Planning Commission Chairperson<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">&nbsp; &nbsp;- Implement=
ation of a formalized agenda-setting procedure where:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;* Th=
e Chairperson submits final agenda items in consultation with staff no late=
r than 10 days before scheduled meetings<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;* St=
aff distributes the final agenda no later than 7 days before regularly sche=
duled meetings<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">The legal and procedural=
 basis for these recommendations is substantial:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">1. Statutory Authority a=
nd Commission Autonomy:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Colorado Revised Statute=
s (C.R.S.) =A7 31-23-204 explicitly grants planning commissions the power t=
o &quot;adopt rules for the transaction of business,&quot; including contro=
l over agenda-setting and scheduling. When town
 staff unilaterally controls these elements, it bypasses the commission's l=
egal mandate to self-govern its procedures. This current setup effectively =
limits the commission's intended autonomy and authority, contrary to the st=
atute's intent for the commission
 to act as an independent, community-focused entity.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">2. Public Representative=
 Role:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Planning commissions wer=
e specifically created as representative bodies to serve the community's pl=
anning and development interests directly. When town staff controls agenda =
priorities and meeting cancellations,
 it risks shifting focus toward internal administrative or political priori=
ties rather than community needs. This arrangement reduces the commission's=
 capacity to function independently and limits its ability to respond direc=
tly to community concerns&#8212;a fundamental
 aspect of its statutory role.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">3. Best Practices in Loc=
al Governance:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Throughout Colorado, pla=
nning commissions typically retain final agenda authority to prevent admini=
strative interference. For example, in Elbert County, the planning commissi=
on sets its own agenda while utilizing
 staff input only for support. This structure reflects the statutory recogn=
ition that planning commissions should operate autonomously. Our current ap=
proach deviates from these established standards, potentially diluting the =
commission's decision-making power
 and public accountability.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">4. Legislative Intent:<o=
:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Colorado law intentional=
ly places planning commissions in a position of public accountability by gr=
anting them statutory authority to manage their own procedural rules. When =
town staff hold power over agendas and
 meeting decisions, it blurs this legal delineation and contradicts the leg=
islative intent to establish planning commissions as independent governing =
bodies. This independence is crucial for the commission to act without undu=
e influence from administrative
 bodies.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Regarding civility and m=
eeting decorum, I would like to address several specific concerns from rece=
nt meetings that need attention to ensure professional discourse and fair p=
articipation:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">1. Points of Order: Duri=
ng our last meeting, town staff called Points of Order. This is procedurall=
y incorrect - Points of Order should only be called by Planning Commission =
members, not staff. This is a fundamental
 rule of parliamentary procedure that needs to be respected.<o:p></o:p></sp=
an></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">2. Professional Discours=
e: During the last meeting, Chairperson Hunter made the comment &quot;I res=
ent Chairperson McCarthy for thinking he is the only one with a family.&quo=
t; This was apparently in response to my request
 to consider school breaks and in-service days in our scheduling. If there =
are concerns about scheduling requests, these should be addressed directly =
and professionally, focusing on the merits of the request rather than perso=
nal accusations.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">3. Non-Verbal Conduct: D=
uring my remarks at the last meeting, Chairperson Hunter was repeatedly sha=
king her head. Such non-verbal expressions of disagreement during another C=
ommissioner's speaking time are unprofessional
 and can create an intimidating environment that discourages open discourse=
=2E<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">4. Meeting Management: A=
t the end of the meeting, while I was speaking, Town Staff (Ruben) muted me=
 mid-sentence when Chairperson Hunter interrupted me. When questioned about=
 this action, the explanation given
 was that it was &quot;a one-sided conversation.&quot; This is deeply conce=
rning for several reasons:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">&nbsp; &nbsp;- Town staf=
f should not be muting Planning Commission members, especially during their=
 allocated speaking time<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">&nbsp; &nbsp;- The decis=
ion to mute should only come from the Chair following proper parliamentary =
procedure<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">&nbsp; &nbsp;- This acti=
on suggests potential bias from town staff favoring certain members and opi=
nions over others<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">&nbsp; &nbsp;- Staff mus=
t maintain strict impartiality in managing meeting logistics<o:p></o:p></sp=
an></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">These incidents indicate=
 a need for:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- Clear guidelines on st=
aff roles during meetings<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- Review of proper parli=
amentary procedure<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- Establishment of profe=
ssional standards for both verbal and non-verbal conduct<o:p></o:p></span><=
/p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- Neutral and consistent=
 application of meeting management procedures<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- Commitment to allowing=
 all Commissioners to complete their thoughts without interruption<o:p></o:=
p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Regarding Agenda Item 4 =
- Discussion and Work on the Comprehensive Plan, specifically the Housing E=
lement, I have serious concerns about transparency and process that need to=
 be addressed:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">1. Process and Transpare=
ncy Issues:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- The draft Housing Elem=
ent introduces 28 new policies that were not part of the extensively vetted=
 Housing Needs Assessment and Action Plan<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- These new policies lac=
k the rigorous documentation, data support, and community input that charac=
terized the Housing Needs Assessment process<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- There has been no expl=
anation provided for how these new policies relate to or derive from the co=
mmunity engagement process<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- The policies lack spec=
ificity and include no implementation examples or resource analysis<o:p></o=
:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">2. Deviation from Board =
Direction:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- The Board of Trustees =
specifically directed that the Housing Needs Assessment and Action Plan be =
incorporated as the Housing Element<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- This directive was dis=
cussed and agreed upon in numerous meetings throughout the past year<o:p></=
o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- The current draft devi=
ates significantly from this direction without explanation<o:p></o:p></span=
></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">3. Community Priority Om=
issions:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- The draft inexplicably=
 omits short-term rental regulation, which received the highest number of v=
otes (21) during our public engagement process<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- This omission directly=
 contradicts documented community priorities and undermines the extensive p=
ublic input process<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">4. Documentation Require=
ments:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Before the Planning Comm=
ission can properly evaluate the Housing Element, we need either:<o:p></o:p=
></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- Detailed documentation=
 justifying each new policy addition, including evidence of community suppo=
rt that meets the same standard of documentation provided in the Housing Ne=
eds Assessment, or<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">- Simple incorporation o=
f the Housing Needs Assessment and Action Plan as originally directed by th=
e Board<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">I cannot support includi=
ng this element in its current form without proper documentation of how the=
se policies relate to our community engagement process and the Housing Need=
s Assessment. Posting policies on a
 website does not constitute the level of transparency and public engagemen=
t our community deserves and expects.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Thank you for considerin=
g these comments. I look forward to our continued work together at the next=
 meeting.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span>=
</p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Respectfully,<o:p></o:p>=
</span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Pete McCarthy<o:p></o:p>=
</span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"color:black">Planning Commissioner<br=
>
<br>
PLEASE PRINT FOR<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
</div>
